  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4241165545" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4241165545" />
    <a title="Jonat" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/130397631-jonat"><img alt="Jonat" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1614434390p2/130397631.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4241165545?book_show_action=true">Nov 20, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jonat" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jonat" href="/user/show/130397631-jonat">Jonat</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/130397631-jonat?shelf=psych-philosophical-fiction">psych-philosophical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/130397631-jonat?shelf=long-books">long-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/130397631-jonat?shelf=french-literature">french-literature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/130397631-jonat?shelf=fav-fiction">fav-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4241165545" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer71510025758384298">The review is longer than when I initially wrote it, so I thought I should make a proper summary of it.<br/><br/>𝐀-/ Melancholy<br/>𝐁-/ The Prose Overall<br/>𝐂-/ The Psychology &amp; The Prose (but more intricately)<br/>D-/ His Selfless Use of Literature<br/>E-/ Time Lost &amp; Time Regained<br/><br/>𝐀-/ 𝐌𝐞𝐥𝐚𝐧𝐜𝐡𝐨𝐥𝐲:<br/><br/>Melancholy is such an innocent and touching state of mind. <br/>When someone gets melancholic, it’s as if, they were always wearing their stoic mask and just, the experience of them dropping it off; - having in mind what horrible though</span>
  <span id="freeText71510025758384298" style="display:none">The review is longer than when I initially wrote it, so I thought I should make a proper summary of it.<br /><br />𝐀-/ Melancholy<br />𝐁-/ The Prose Overall<br />𝐂-/ The Psychology &amp; The Prose (but more intricately)<br />D-/ His Selfless Use of Literature<br />E-/ Time Lost &amp; Time Regained<br /><br />𝐀-/ 𝐌𝐞𝐥𝐚𝐧𝐜𝐡𝐨𝐥𝐲:<br /><br />Melancholy is such an innocent and touching state of mind. <br />When someone gets melancholic, it’s as if, they were always wearing their stoic mask and just, the experience of them dropping it off; - having in mind what horrible thoughts led this stoic person to such honesty and vulnerability.. -<br /><br /> The process of seeing someone being melancholic is like attending at the rebirth of an adult into a child, because of *the innocence* the atmosphere of their very gesture convey, to open up like this to such intimate feelings that could make people find you ridicule to linger onto… this switch from stoic to innocence, from adult to child <br /><br />In my head, Melancholy is the mystical metamorphosis of all this into one.<br /><br />Because of Time, Everything in life is in a continuous mutating process, and as Proust realized it, it enhanced the amount of things in his life affected by his melancholy. <br /><br />I’m talking about people he spent too few time with, people he’s spent too much time with, their behaviors at a specific moment in his mind, events he’s been through, events he missed out on, objects, places(from Combray his home town to the tiniest object in his bedroom), 4 thousand pages on Proust being melancholic about all these things broke my heart… in a bittersweet and comforting way due to: <br /><br />-on one side : his touching prose, that feels like a mother is telling a bednight story to her baby,<br /><br />-on another hand, due to the knowledge that, he will gain his 𝘵𝘪𝘮𝘦 𝘭𝘰𝘴𝘵 by doing such a detailed and honest retelling of his life…<br /><br />𝐀.𝟏-/𝐖𝐡𝐲 𝐨𝐮𝐫 𝐡𝐞𝐚𝐫𝐭/𝐩𝐞𝐫𝐬𝐨𝐧𝐚𝐥𝐢𝐭𝐲 𝐜𝐡𝐚𝐧𝐠𝐞𝐬 𝐨𝐯𝐞𝐫 𝐭𝐢𝐦𝐞<br /><br />Yes we know that “time affect us”, but how ? <br />For Proust, It’s a continuous phenomena of our eyes.<br /><br />As our eyes perceive a subject, a materiality, <br /><br />The sensation we feel maybe as we see the Eiffel Tower and feel marvelled to it , it’s because our eyes, these lentils, converted the Tower (something material) as a positive memory (something immaterial within us)<br /><br />The sensations/impressions we receive from a material occurence is converted as memories within us, and these memories constantly meddle with our soul (because both are immaterial entities), <br /><br />and *this* is why humans constantly change over time.<br /><br />Our eyes are constantly converting what it sees into memories and it’s a never ending process of our soul constantly assimilating/merging with these impressions.<br /><br /><br />𝐀-𝟐/ 𝐖𝐡𝐲 𝐝𝐨 𝐩𝐞𝐨𝐩𝐥𝐞 𝐠𝐞𝐭 𝐦𝐞𝐥𝐚𝐧𝐜𝐡𝐨𝐥𝐢𝐜 ? <br /><br />Following the first theory, As we see certain landscapes during maybe on holidays, their specific shapes and colours are converted into memories within us, and when ,<br /><br /><br /> as time goes on, we stumble across these same landscapes during maybe the next holidays , those same shapes and colours are converted into memories within us, and those memories will detect and find memories within me from the previous holidays, that is, memories from 𝐚𝐧𝐚𝐥𝐨𝐠𝐨𝐮𝐬 𝐦𝐚𝐭𝐭𝐞𝐫, <br />which will consequently “wakes up” memories from the first holiday, creating a vivid nostalgia, melancholic sensation from how I’ve felt during the first holiday<br /><br /><br /><br />𝐁-/ 𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐫𝐨𝐬𝐞: 𝐎𝐯𝐞𝐫𝐚𝐥𝐥<br /><br />It was sometimes difficult for me to stop reading this book. <br /><br />His prose made me feel like I'm on a river and getting transported by it without having to do anything. A subtle and soothing sound during my river trip… no matter the saddest experience, it is told in such calming phrasing and tone that gives me the impression of someone telling me a poem, despite the language in itself not arranged poetically. <br /><br />These hollow and sweet sensations of a delicate voice that sound like whispers.. made me purposely seek for silent places to fully enjoy this never-ending lullaby prose<br /><br />This book is often like the experience I have with subtle music. It’s something I would happily be willing to re-read the same way I re-listen to a song. Despite its sometimes dense topics, it has it in it to lighten them in order to pull out the vulnerability in everything he writes about.<br /><br />—-<br />𝐂-/ 𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐬𝐲𝐜𝐡𝐨𝐥𝐨𝐠𝐲 &amp; 𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐫𝐨𝐬𝐞 (𝐛𝐮𝐭 𝐦𝐨𝐫𝐞 𝐢𝐧𝐭𝐫𝐢𝐜𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐥𝐲)<br /><br />It is sometimes hard to stop reading, yes, but especially when it comes to interactions between the narrator, women and nature.<br /><br />You just get carried into the current of this river of human relations and you have to carefully slow down your pace, you have to float and take better control of your body into this river in order to *savour* the delightful richness implemented into these depictions. <br /><br />Theatrical depictions of all the tiniest intricate behaviors of every day’s relations, And although Proust’s grasp of their psychology is impeccable, <br /><br />what I like most is the philosophical touch (the universal truths he squeezes in each of these behaviors, repliques, talks), I just love how deep he goes into the psychology of his characters, while also laying out some traits similar to all of us, enriched by a comic, theatrical or poetic charm… <br /><br />I always get such a divine revelation within me whenever an author writes about a specific feeling that I’ve always felt but never really noticed its presence: <br /><br />almost like that feeling was always asleep within me and the author just wakes “him” up through gorgeous and detailed writing of it<br /><br />But not only that. His imageries not only beautifies his ideas but they are meaningful and expanded. <br /><br />He tenderly undress their soul, in order to reveal fully both their contextual depth and their final poetic form(s)! - creating an effect of packed short story within a story, through charming imageries , whose (those imageries) themselves compliment an initial idea (these universal truths).<br /><br /><br />-A clear example of this- being about: the effect of jealousy and how it revives within us the ferocity of our first negative assumptions about a person :<br /><br /><br />“(…) But hadn't I guessed it from the first day in Balbec?<br /><br /> Had I not guessed in Albertine one of those girls under whose fleshly envelope throb more hidden beings, I am not saying that in a deck of cards still in its box, than in a closed cathedral or a theater before that one does not enter, but only in the immense and renewed crowd?<br /><br /> Not only so many beings, but the desire, the luscious memory, the uneasy research of so many beings.<br /> (…)<br /><br /> And now that she had once said to me: “Mme Vinteuil”, I would have liked not to tear off her dress to see her body, but through her body to see all this notepad of her memories and her next ardent rendezvous. ”<br /><br />𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐰𝐚𝐲 𝐡𝐞 𝐦𝐚𝐧𝐢𝐩𝐮𝐥𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐬 𝐭𝐡𝐞𝐬𝐞 𝐬𝐮𝐛𝐣𝐞𝐜𝐭𝐬: Albertine’s body containing notepads (allegory for her secrets) , and now he wants to open her body figuratively in order to see all her notepads/agenda where she "wrote" so many secrets date in there... <br /><br />—<br />-How psychology is often used:<br /><br />I often find the use of psychology in novels to be too… “on paper”, “robotic”.. as if it follows a script. But in real life, even family members that we’ve barely interacted with can plummet our mood into severe sadness feeling.. <br /><br />of course the latter is more difficult to pull off in novels because, for the reader to share the grieving sadness of a character, the reader needs to see moments of those two together, prior their death in order to maximize our empathy towards the character’s sorrow. <br /><br /><br />YET, in this book, regarding his grand-mother’s passing, they didn’t need to do this *robotic* script to make us feel the narrator’s sorrow, thanks to Proust’s touching prose for dozens of pages.<br /><br /> Not only that, but this felt like a real experience in the real world. So I thank this book for pulling out all the emotional fragrance of certain frequent real life’s sad experience that i find daunting to effectively pull in a novel (due to lack of character interactions prior for such experience).<br /><br />The emotional impact doesn’t come from a buildup shown to the reader prior, but moreso from the way Proust integrates so well the narrator’s memories of his grand mother at that moment. <br /><br />The Characterization and the climax overlap at the same time while still playing with that overarching theme of uncovering past memories. That theme harmonizes bittersweetly with this unconventional (in a novel), yet realistic portrayal of grief.<br /><br />And just because I love this passage of it so much, please read this :<br /><br />“(…) The big day woke me up. <br /><br />But I couldn't bear to watch those waves of the sea that my grandmother could once gaze upon for hours;<br /> the new image of their indifferent beauty was immediately complemented by the idea that she did not see them; <br /><br />I wanted to cover my ears with their noise, because now the luminous fullness of the beach was creating a void in my heart; <br />everything seemed to say to me like those alleys and these lawns of a public garden where I had once lost it, when I was a little child: “We did not see it”, <br /><br />and under the roundness of the pale and divine sky I felt oppressed as under a huge bluish bell closing a horizon where my grandmother was not ..”<br /><br /><br />——<br /><br /> (another last rambling about the prose)<br /><br />I know I have used the word “tenderness” a lot, but it's just that- the constant lack of *stiff* feeling when reading his even long sentences .. really sparkle within me a new aspiration towards my writing skills.<br /><br />I mean, look at this..<br /><br />“I could caress it, run my hands over it for a long time, but, as if I had wielded a stone which encloses the dirt of immemorial oceans or the ray of a star, I felt that I was only touching the closed envelope of a being who from within had access to infinity.<br /><br /> How much I have suffered from this position in which nature has placed us, which, by instituting the division of bodies, did not think of making possible the interpenetration of souls...”<br /><br />𝐃-/ 𝐇𝐢𝐬 𝐬𝐞𝐥𝐟𝐥𝐞𝐬𝐬 𝐮𝐬𝐞 𝐨𝐟 𝐥𝐢𝐭𝐞𝐫𝐚𝐭𝐮𝐫𝐞<br /><br />Due to the length of the review and the immense importance of this part, I have dedicated my Swann’s Review to relate it: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4315017284">https://www.goodreads.com/review/show...</a><br /><br />Literature is used in 2 antithesis goals on this novel : a selfless one and a personal one. <br /><br />The selfless one is the one stated on the link above, the selfish one is for regaining his time lost! <br /><br /><br />E-/𝐅𝐢𝐧𝐚𝐥 𝐏𝐚𝐫𝐭: 𝐓𝐢𝐦𝐞 𝐋𝐨𝐬𝐭 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐓𝐢𝐦𝐞 𝐑𝐞𝐠𝐚𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐝<br /><br />-seeing foreseen happiness into something and actually feeling happiness when “experiencing” that thing are two complete separate things, yet always so linked in life.<br /><br />He wanted to find pleasure at Balbec, he wanted to find pleasure by living with Albertine.. we remember how much he extrapolated the foreseen happiness of what those two experiences will bring to him. <br /><br />But why did both “disappointed” him ? <br /><br /><br />“The Time Lost” through seeking such *predicted* happiness from how we viewed it in the past , by enjoying it in the present, <br /><br />in our belief that it will be fulfilled through the action of consuming what we predicted in a past moment… <br /><br />Those disappointments take their roots into: the endless manifestations of the powerlessness that we have to realize ourselves in material enjoyment, in effective action. <br /><br />For Proust, trying to do so, trying to “realize ourselves” in material enjoyment, is Time Lost. <br /><br /><br />You know when you start seeing maybe Paris, the city on TV ads and think about how much life would be so much better there and so on, but when you actually come Living in Paris- you experience disappointment compared to what your thoughts made you foresee ? <br /><br /><br />The same things kept happening to him by (for example), these positive impressions that he felt through the sight of the bell towers of MartinVille ( a city), instead of seeking through it materially, the right way to pull out the happiness I’ve felt from it was to convert those sensations spiritually… that is through creating writings of it. That is litterature.<br />.<br />.<br />.<br />but WHY ?<br /><br />On the moment something is perceived by us, they become within us (in our memory), something “immaterial”.<br /><br /><br />I mean don’t you find this fascinating ? <br /><br />We see material things with our eyes at a given moment, and they are automatically converted into immateriality within us (as memory) at that given moment. <br /><br />But We assume that since, we still don't see that material thing particularly different physically compared to that memory of our past, since its appearance is still the same, we assume that we will have similar experiences than how we've felt from the past with it.<br /><br /> Yet, it is that immaterial thing (those memories that were able to immortalize our impressions of a material entity at a given moment), it is these memories, that produce us a feeling of foreseen happiness into that material thing. <br /><br />But since we focus on the visible world, human beings pursue the fulfillment of that happiness through material actions… in vain.<br /><br />It is not the material action with that thing that will produce me happiness (since material objects are continuously altered/mutating in time).<br /><br /> it’s by reaching out within me to the immaterial version (of the material I saw at that moment) that will produce me happiness. This. I love this.<br /><br /><br />Time is the reason why we can’t attain fulfilmment of our impressions through material realization,<br /> <br />because of how it alters our mood, other people’s mood, but also the conditions of things, and also the conditions we were in when getting a specific impression. Time is always moving and, for this, an impression we feel from a material object is never going to be fulfilled to the same way/intensity through material enjoyment of it, due to Time’s constant influence on things.<br /><br />Thankfully for us, these impressions are stored in our memories but sadly over time they get hidden. <br />We don’t *feel* these heartwarming sensations on command in our everyday life, and worse, we tend to think the enjoyment of these impressions can only be found in the enjoyment of the material thing that created it when we’ve looked at it.<br /><br />But the thing is, that material thing doesn’t exist anymore, because the mere fact that Time is everly moving, Seeing something at a specific second, in a specific place, with specific conditions and in a specific mood, is going to be a different experience when seeing that thing two minutes after. It’s not the *same* material anymore.<br /><br /> And just because of that fact, we are expecting an enjoyment off a material that isn't the same anymore.. in vain.<br /><br />Unfortunately, this is hardly perceptible in the visible world.<br /><br />Nothing is more painful than this opposition between the alteration of beings and the fixity of memory, <br />when we understand that, what has kept so much freshness in our memory can no longer have in life, <br />that we cannot, outside, bring us closer, to what seems so beautiful inside us🥺, to what excites in us a desire,<br /><br />that by seeking him in a being of the same age, that would mean to seek him in another being😔.<br /><br />As he was tired of experimenting his impossibility to attain in the real world what was within him, Proust decided to go on a quest of finding them. <br /><br />And the process of creating art allowed him to have a trip within the depths of his own self.<br /><br /> By writing all those tiniest details about his life all over this massive novel, by digging through them as a gold miner, he not only was able to find hidden truths about himself but also able to perceive these buried memories in all their tender warmth of his past. The joy of finally experiencing these impressions. <br /><br />Beautiful prose about love is always a delight to read, but in this case, not only it’s my favoritr showcase in terms of prose but his dreamy prose is also meaningful towards the core theme of the novel. <br /><br />Him, expanding for dozens of pages about his voluptuous feelings towards Albertine ,is him finally re-experiencing those sweet sensations from his past. He wasn’t able to feel the same bewitching and heartwarming impressions during his relationship with Albertine over time .. (for reasons stated above) <br /><br />I’m sure he had so much bubbly emotions writing all these flowery lines about his passions of his first meet-up with Albertine, of his fresh memories at Colbray, of his childhood.. who never yearned at some point to be thrown back onto our childhood again?<br /><br /> The thought of this makes me want to re-read these early sections of the novel, just to appreciate the new emotional weight they have; now that I know how much remembering fully these memories mean to the author. Also, aren't they all just gorgeously written ? <br />I've already started my re-read journey and it's been a delight.<br /><br /><br /><br />Proust found a way to circumvent Time, the antagonist of everyone’s life, before his death.<br />Never have I seen a work of literature given such a shine to the importance of this very literature we all consume, its importance that it can have in our life.<br /><br />"Nothing is more painful than this opposition between the alteration of beings and the fixity of memory" <br /><br />Maybe one day, when I will get depressed enough at another deception of my life, I will revolve at writing a work of art,<br /><br /> whose plot allows me to focus on the beauty of how I’ve felt when staring at a material entity (a girl, a city/place I really wanted to live, etc) that gave me this much positive feeling in my real life,<br /><br />𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐫𝐞𝐠𝐚𝐢𝐧 𝐦𝐲 𝐭𝐢𝐦𝐞 𝐥𝐨𝐬𝐭 𝐢𝐧 𝐢𝐭𝐬 𝐩𝐮𝐫𝐬𝐮𝐞 𝐨𝐮𝐭𝐬𝐢𝐝𝐞 𝐨𝐟 𝐦𝐲 𝐬𝐨𝐮𝐥<br /><br />- À La Recherche Du Temps Perdu by Marcel Proust : 10/10.</span>
  <a data-text-id="71510025758384298" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


