<div id="review_396503859" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/396503859" />
    <a title="AC" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1655437-ac"><img alt="AC" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1228702469p2/1655437.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/396503859?book_show_action=true">Jul 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="AC" class="user" itemprop="url" name="AC" href="/user/show/1655437-ac">AC</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9782070754922" href="/book/show/167803._la_recherche_du_temps_perdu">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1655437-ac?shelf=proust">proust</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1655437-ac?shelf=novels-french">novels-french</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer396503859" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12815437328802512339">According to this record, it took me 8 years to read the whole of Proust, having read Swann’s Way in August 2012. But that is not really the whole story. For I began reading Proust some 45 years years ago.<br/><br/>Of course, I spent a generation reading other things and doing scholarship, and reading almost no literature... but that is another story.<br/><br/>Rather than comment on Proust, I will offer a word of advice to those who still find this mountain impossible to climb.<br/><br/>I read Swann’s Way at least 4 times. M</span>
  <span id="freeText12815437328802512339" style="display:none">According to this record, it took me 8 years to read the whole of Proust, having read Swann’s Way in August 2012. But that is not really the whole story. For I began reading Proust some 45 years years ago.<br /><br />Of course, I spent a generation reading other things and doing scholarship, and reading almost no literature... but that is another story.<br /><br />Rather than comment on Proust, I will offer a word of advice to those who still find this mountain impossible to climb.<br /><br />I read Swann’s Way at least 4 times. Maybe 5. Once, carefully, many years ago..., twice in 2012 — I had to read each section twice to get it. And then again a few years ago, when I determined for the umpteenth time to finish.<br /><br />I read Within a Budding Grove many years ago, then read it twice a couple of years ago..., and then began again with the Balbec section this time, in January. <br /><br />I had read parts of the Guermantes Way as a youth — that’s apparently where I had gotten stuck — and then slogged through it this time —. It took me 2-3 months. But by that point, I knew vols. I-II so well, that as soon as I launched on Sodom and Gomorrah — it just flowed. Both plot and prose. <br /><br />And all this, partially thanks to living indoors during the year of the plague.<br /><br />One other point — two scenes that had vividly lodged themselves in my memory 45 years ago, when reading this as a youth..., it turns out... are not even in the book. <br /><br />I have to thank especially Kalliope, though we do not speak much any more, for setting an example with her Year of Reading Proust — and whose perseverance was a constant goad and shame to me. <br /><br />In the end, I can say that both the effort and the refusal to get knocked down was all worth it — in multiples..., esp. as Vols. IV-VII have so many astonishing surprises in store for one.<br /><br />That’s enough from me... read Proust. Certainly before you die.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12815437328802512339" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


